{{Infobox museum | name = Sousse Archaeological Museum | native_name = Musée archéologique de Sousse | native_name_lang = المتحف الأثري بسوسة | image = Sousse neptune.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | alt = | map_type = | map_caption = | map_alt = | coordinates = | established = 1951 (reopen in 2012 after reorganisation of the collections and restoration of the building were completed) | location = [[Sousse]], [[Sousse Governorate|Governorate of Sousse]], [[Tunisia]] | type = [[museum#Archaeology museums|Archaeological museum]] | collection = [[Phoenicia]]n ([[Punic]], [[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginian]]), [[Ancient Rome|Roman]], [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]], [[Christian]] | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | publictransit = | car_park = | network = | website = }} The '''Sousse Archaeological Museum''' ([[Tunisian Arabic]]: المتحف الأثري بسوسة) is an [[archaeological museum]] located in [[Sousse]], [[Sousse Governorate]], [[Tunisia]].
==The Museum== The [[museum]] is housed in the [[Kasbah]] of Sousse's [[Medina of Sousse, Tunisia|Medina]], which was founded in the 11th century AD.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.patrimoinedetunisie.com.tn/eng/musees/sousse.php}}</ref> It was established in 1951. The museum reopened its doors to the public in 2012, after the collections were rearranged and the edifice was renovated. It contains the second largest collection of [[mosaics]] in the world after that of the [[Bardo National Museum]] in the capital [[Tunis]].
== The Collections==
Some votive stelae and urns displayed in the [[punic]] room date from as early as the 7th century BC. Artefacts dating from the [[Ancient history|antiquity]] up to the 2nd century BC were discovered by [[France|French]] [[Archeology|archeologist]] [[Pierre Cintas]] in the [[Tophet]] of [[Sousse]] and in the [[Sanctuary]] of [[Baal Hammon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.patrimoinedetunisie.com.tn/eng/musees/sousse.php}}</ref> In addition, it contains some gorgeous mosaics depicting mythological figures, such as the "Head of [[Medusa]]", Face of [[Oceanus]], [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] on his [[sea-chariot]], or Nilotic scene to name but a few. A [[baptismal font]], covered with [[mosaics]] and found at [[Bqalta]], is on display alongside some [[Christian]] themed decorative terracotta tablets. The museum also exhibits some marbel statues from the Roman epoch such as the bust of [[emperor]] [[Hadrian]] and the statue of Roman fertility and manhood [[god]] [[Periapus]] with his sizeable [[phallus]]... Some funerary artifacts are also part of the collection, they were discovered at [[Hadrumetum]] (Roman Sousse)'s [[catacombs]] as well as the [[Catacomb of Good Shepherd]], and the [[Catacomb of Hermes]]... The museum also features some local [[pottery]] from Greece found within the Punic tombs at El-Kasabah: oil lamps, and some marble funerary [[epitaphs]] engraved in [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[Latin]] languages, and among these epitaphs can be found the famous marble tablet engraved with the figure of the "[[Good Shepherd]]" after which the place of the discovery was named.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/tunisia/central-tunisia/sousse/sights/museums-galleries/sousse-archaeological-museum}}</ref>
